29 Sec. 22e. (1) The authority, in cooperation with the
KAS H05885'25 (H-1) sog07q

16
1 department of treasury, shall establish, implement, and administer
2 a housing opportunity tax credit program to encourage the
3 development of qualified projects in this state.
4 (2) For award cycles beginning on and after January 1, 2027,
5 the authority shall, in conjunction with applications received
6 under section 22b, accept applications for housing opportunity tax
7 credits under this section. Subject to the award cycle cap under
8 subsection (4) and the limitations under this section, the
9 authority shall not issue an award for an annual housing
10 opportunity tax credit under this program for a qualified project
11 that exceeds the lesser of the following:
12 (a) The amount necessary for the financial feasibility of the
13 qualified project.
14 (b) The adjusted annual federal credit amount for the
15 qualified project.
16 (3) A person seeking a housing opportunity tax credit under
17 this section shall submit an application in a form and manner as
18 prescribed by the authority. The authority shall review completed
19 applications for housing opportunity tax credits received for 4%
20 qualified projects on a first-come, first-served basis. The
21 authority shall treat all complete applications received on the
22 same day as having been received simultaneously. If the
23 applications received for 4% qualified projects exceed the portion
24 of the award cycle cap set aside under subsection (4)(b) and (c) on
25 any day, the authority shall establish an evaluation methodology to
26 determine which of the 4% qualified projects applications are
27 approved and issued an award of a housing opportunity tax credit.
28 The evaluation methodology required under this subsection must be
29 limited to factors that maximize efficient unit production,
KAS H05885'25 (H-1) sog07q

17
1 including, but not limited to, each of the following:
2 (a) The amount of the housing opportunity tax credit requested
3 for each unit under the proposed qualified project.
4 (b) The number of units to be preserved or created under the
5 proposed qualified project.
6 (c) The estimated development period of the proposed qualified
7 project from the initial award to placing the proposed qualified
8 project in service.
9 (4) For the 2027 award cycle, the authority shall not allocate
10 a total of more than the base annual amount of $42,000,000.00 for
11 housing opportunity tax credits under this section. For each award
12 cycle after the 2027 award cycle, to determine the award cycle cap
13 for that award cycle, the base annual amount for the immediately
14 preceding award cycle must be adjusted annually by the percentage
15 increase in the United States Consumer Price Index for the
16 immediately preceding calendar year. The total amount of all
17 housing opportunity tax credits for which an award is issued under
18 this section must not exceed the award cycle cap for any award
19 cycle. For each application window, the authority shall approve and
20 allocate not less than 45% of the award cycle cap for that award
21 cycle to qualified projects to the extent that the authority
22 receives a sufficient number of applications. If, at the end of an
23 application window, the authority has not received a sufficient
24 number of completed applications to allocate the amount set aside
25 under subdivision (a), (b), (c), or (d), the authority may
